        <p>
        <h2 id="intro"><red>INTRODUCTION:</red> WELCOME TO WEB PROGRAMMING!</h2>
        HTML, or the HyperText Markup Language, is the core language that all webpages use.
        ...
        <h3 id="instructions"><red>INSTRUCTIONS ON USING AND UNDERSTANDING THIS WEBSITE</red></h3>
        Before you begin learning to program and actively programming, there are a few instructions that need to be addressed regarding the use and comprehension of this website. First, examples of code are read <span class="inline-code">like this,</span> with a blue background and in the appropriate text style. Paragraphs of code are defined similar to the previous example:
        <div class="code" style="width:auto;">
        Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipisicing elit, <br>
        sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua.<br>
        Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris <br>
        nisi ut aliquip ex ea commodo consequat.<br>
        </div>
        Also, there are a few interactive web editors that act as instant practice. Operating these is simple (especially for those of you who have used <a href="http://www.khanacademy.org" target="_blank" style="color:#888;">Khan Academy</a>'s HTML editor before): type in the web code on the left side and the result will come on the right.<br>
        One note: the HTML editors are
        </p>
        <hr>
        <p>
          <h2 id="les1"><red>LESSON 1:</red> INTRO TO HTML</h2>
          Welcome to HTML! HTML uses "tags," or words inside angle brackets (&lt;&gt;)
          The first things you will learn are the most basic tags that are required in every webpage. The first one, <span class="inline-code">&lt;html&gt;</span>, is the very basis for all other tags. It goes at the beginning and end of the webpage, like the sample below:<br><br>
          <div class="code" style="width: 250px;">
            &lt;html&gt;<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;head&gt;<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;...<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/head&gt;<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;body&gt;<br/>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;...<br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/body&gt;<br/>&lt;html&gt;<br/>
          </div><br>
          The tags <span class="inline-code">&lt;head&gt;</span> and <span class="inline-code">&lt;body&gt;</span>, which are second-level tags (they are the second 'tab' up), are also required. <span class="inline-code">&lt;head&gt;</span> is where you put the webpage title, styles (later), scripts (later), and <span class="inline-code">&lt;meta&gt;</span> (we will cover this soon) information. The <span class="inline-code">&lt;body&gt;</span> tag is where the webpage content goes.
          <br>
        </p>
